:"FIRST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Philip \" Fychan\" ap Gwilym was born about 1211, in Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales, his father, Gwilym ap Maredudd, was 38 and his mother, Margred Verch Meurig Goch, was 18. He had at least 1 son with Elen ferch Trahaearn."},"et":{"about 1211–":"umbes 1211–Surnud","1211–Male":"1211–Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1174–Male":"1174–Surnud","1195–Female":"1195–Surnud","1211":"1211","1220":"1220","about 1211":"umbes 1211","1174":"1174","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","about 1240":"umbes 1240","Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1211–":"noin 1211–Kuollut","1211–Male":"1211–Kuollut","1220–Female":"1220–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1174–Male":"1174–Kuollut","1195–Female":"1195–Kuollut","1211":"1211","1220":"1220","about 1211":"noin 1211","1174":"1174","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","about 1240":"noin 1240","Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1211–":"environ 1211–Décédé","1211–Male":"1211–Décédé","1220–Female":"1220–Décédée","1240–Male":"1240–Décédé","1174–Male":"1174–Décédé","1195–Female":"1195–Décédée","1211":"1211","1220":"1220","about 1211":"environ 1211","1174":"1174","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","about 1240":"environ 1240","Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Philip \" Fychan\" ap Gwilym est né environ 1211, à Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Galles, son père, Gwilym ap Maredudd, avait 38 ans et sa mère, Margred Verch Meurig Goch, avait 18 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Elen ferch Trahaearn."},"de":{"about 1211–":"um 1211–Verstorben","1211–Male":"1211–Verstorben","1220–Female":"1220–Verstorben","1240–Male":"1240–Verstorben","1174–Male":"1174–Verstorben","1195–Female":"119